Department of Justice Seal DEPARTMENT OF JUSTICE CIVIL RIGHTS DIVISION ENFORCEMENT AND OUTREACH FOLLOWING THE SEPTEMBER 11 ATTACKS Since September 11, the Civil Rights Division of the U.S. Department of Justice has been involved in the investigation and prosecution of alleged incidents involving violence or threats against Arab Americans, Muslim Americans, Sikh Americans, South-Asian Americans, and those perceived to be members of these communities.
The Division has also been involved in outreach efforts to these communities to provide information about government services.
With respect to the investigation and prosecution of alleged incidents involving violence or threats, the Civil Rights Division, the Federal Bureau of Investigation, and U.S. Attorneys' offices have investigated approximately 380 such incidents since September 11.
The incidents have consisted of telephone, internet, mail, and face-to-face threats; minor assaults as well as assaults with dangerous weapons and assaults resulting in serious injury and death; and vandalism, shootings, and bombings directed at homes, businesses, and places of worship.
Several experienced attorneys in the Civil Rights Division's Criminal Section have been tasked to intake all new allegations and to monitor those investigations that are opened to ensure uniform decision-making in the initiation of federal investigations and prosecutions and to optimize resource allocation.
Approximately 70 state and local criminal prosecutions have been initiated against approximately 80 defendants, many after coordination between federal and local prosecutors and investigators.
Federal charges have been brought in 10 cases involving 12 defendants, and the Civil Rights Division and U.S. Attorneys' offices are working together on those cases:
(1) On March 28, 2002, the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Northern District of Florida filed a criminal complaint against Charles D. Franklin under 18 U.S.C. 247 for driving his pickup truck into the door of the Islamic Center Mosque in Tallahassee, Florida.
Franklin was indicted on the same charge on April 16, 2002, and a superseding indictment was returned on June 18, 2002.
(2) On February 14, 2002, the U.S. Attorney's Office for the District of Massachusetts filed a criminal information against Zachary J. Rolnik under 18 U.S.C. 245 for placing a telephone call to Dr. James J. Zogby, the president of the Arab American Institute, in which Rolnik threatened to kill Dr. Zogby and his children.
On June 6, 2002, Rolnik pleaded guilty to the charge.
(3) On December 12, 2001, the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Central District of California filed a criminal complaint against Irving David Rubin and Earl Leslie Krugel under 18 U.S.C. 371, 844, and 924 for conspiring to damage and destroy, by means of an explosive, the King Fahd mosque and for possessing an explosive bomb to carry out the conspiracy.
On January 10, 2002, Rubin and Krugel were indicted under 18 U.S.C. 371, 2332, 844, 924, 373, 922, and 5861, which additionally included charges related to the defendants' alleged attempts to damage and destroy, by means of an explosive, the office of the Muslim Public Affairs Council and the district office of U.S. Representative Darrell Issa.
Press releases: December 12, 2001, January 10, 2002.
(4) On December 5, 2001, the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Eastern District of Michigan filed a criminal information against Justin Scott-Priestley Bolen under 42 U.S.C. 3631 for placing a threatening phone call to the answering machine of a Pakistani American.
On February 6, 2002, Bolen pleaded guilty to violating 42 U.S.C. 3631, and he was sentenced to a term of 10 months in prison on May 14, 2002.
Press release: May, 15, 2002.
(5) On November 9, 2001, the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Western District of Wisconsin filed a criminal complaint against Wesley Fritts under 18 U.S.C. 876 for sending fake anthrax and anti-religious references in the mail to a restaurant and to a U.S. Air Force recruiting station.
On November 28, 2001, Fritts was indicted under 18 U.S.C. 876 and 2332.
On March 4, 2002, Fritts pleaded guilty to violating 18 U.S.C. 2332, and on May 13, 2002, he was sentenced to a term of 21 months in prison.
(6) On November 7, 2001, the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Western District of Wisconsin indicted Thomas Iverson under 18 U.S.C. 844 for making two threatening phone calls, one to a Jordanian American threatening to burn down his liquor store in Beloit, and another to 9-1-1 threatening to bomb the same store.
On January 31, 2002, Iverson pleaded guilty to violating 18 U.S.C. 844, and on April 12, 2002, he was sentenced to 27 months incarceration.
(7) On October 9, 2001, the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Western District of Texas indicted Joe Luis Montes under 47 U.S.C. 844.
On December 4, 2001, the U.S. Attorney's Office dismissed the indictment and filed a superseding information against Montes under 47 U.S.C. 223 for making a telephone bomb threat against South Asians working at a truck stop.
On December 4, 2001, Montes pleaded guilty to violating 47 U.S.C. 223, and on January 30, 2002, he was sentenced to two years probation and a $500 fine.
(8) On September 27, 2001, the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Eastern District of Tennessee filed a criminal complaint against Jason Brandon Kitts and Travis Lynn Kitts under 18 U.S.C. 245 for brutally assaulting two persons of Indian descent who managed a motel.
(9) On September 26, 2001, the U.S. Attorney's Office for the District of Utah indicted James Herrick under 18 U.S.C. 245 for filling two glass jars with pillow stuffing and gasoline, placing them against a wall of a Pakistani-American owned restaurant, and lighting the jars, which damaged the exterior wall of the restaurant.
On October 24, 2001, Herrick pleaded guilty to violating 18 U.S.C. 245, and on January 7, 2002, he was sentenced to 51 months incarceration.
(10) On September 26, 2001, the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Western District of Washington indicted Patrick Cunningham under 18 U.S.C. 844, 247, and 924 for shooting at two Muslim worshipers and for dousing two cars with gasoline in an attempt to ignite them and cause an explosion that would damage or destroy the Islamic Idriss Mosque.
On May 9, 2002, Cunningham pleaded guilty to violating 18 U.S.C. 247 and 924.
Press releases: September 26, 2001, May 9, 2002.
In addition, the Civil Rights Division and the U.S. Attorney's offices continue to coordinate with local prosecutors in instances where cases are being prosecuted locally - and where there are also potential federal crimes that have not been charged - to consider whether plea bargains can resolve both local and federal criminal liability.
With respect to community outreach, Assistant Attorney General Ralph F. Boyd, Jr. directed the Civil Rights Division's National Origin Working Group to help combat the post-September 11 discriminatory backlash against Arab Americans, Muslim Americans, Sikh Americans, South-Asian Americans, and those perceived to be members of these groups, by referring allegations of discrimination to the appropriate authorities, by conducting educational outreach to vulnerable communities to provide information about Civil Rights Division services, and by working with other Department of Justice components and governmental agencies to ensure the effective provision of services to vulnerable communities.
Since September 11, Assistant Attorney General Boyd has spoken out against bias-motivated violence and threats of violence, and he has met frequently with leaders of Arab-American, Muslim-American, Sikh-American, and South-Asian American organizations.
* The Assistant Attorney General's first such meeting occurred on September 13, 2001, the same day he issued a statement that "[a]ny threats of violence or discrimination against Arab or Muslim Americans or Americans of South Asian descents are not just wrong and un-American, but also are unlawful and will be treated as such."
Among the attendees at this meeting were Dr. James Zogby, President, Arab American Institute; George Salem, Chairman, Arab American Institute; and Dr. Ziad Asali, President, American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee.
* On September 18, 2001, Assistant Attorney General Boyd, along with Robert Jordan and Thomas Reynolds of the FBI Civil Rights Unit and Jonathan Chace and George Henderson of the Justice Department's Community Relations Service, met with leaders of Arab-American, Muslim-American, Sikh-American, and South-Asian American organizations, including Dr. James Zogby, George Salem, Dr. Ziad Asali, and Amardeep Sing Bhalla, Director, Office of Legal Affairs, Sikh Coalition.
* Assistant Attorney General Boyd spoke at the "Vigil for Community Healing, Tolerance, and Unity" at the Japanese-American Memorial in Washington, D.C. on September 25, 2001.
The event was attended by members of Congress and by leaders of Arab-American, Muslim-American, Sikh-American, South-Asian American, Jewish, and Christian organizations.
* On September 29, 2001, the Assistant Attorney General spoke at an Arab American Institute event in McLean, Virginia.
* On October 5, 2001, Assistant Attorney General Boyd and Robert Jordan from the FBI Civil Rights Unit, were guests on a television show hosted by Dr. James Zogby.
During the show, the guests answered questions from callers in the United States and the Middle East regarding bias-motivated crimes and the terrorism investigation.
* Assistant Attorney General Boyd attended a meeting hosted by Attorney General John Ashcroft at the Department of Justice with leaders of Arab-American, Muslim-American, Sikh-American, and South-Asian American organizations on October 16, 2001.
* On November 20, 2001, Assistant Attorney General Boyd spoke at a Civil Rights Division-organized community forum in Dearborn, Michigan to provide information and to answer questions regarding federal civil rights protections, including complaint filing procedures, as well as federal efforts to combat discriminatory backlash.
Civil Rights Division community forums were also held in Chicago on October 9, 2001; Arlington, Virginia on January 16, 2002; Phoenix, Arizona on May 8, 2002; and Atlanta, Georgia on July 11, 2002.
* The Assistant Attorney General accompanied the Attorney General to an Iftaar dinner sponsored by the Islamic Institute at the Islamic Center in Washington, D.C. on November 27, 2001.
* On December 5, 2001, the Assistant Attorney General and Robert Jordan and Thomas Reynolds from the FBI Civil Rights Unit met with Dr. Ziad Asali regarding consensual interviews of immigrant men.
* On December 6, 2001, Assistant Attorney General Boyd spoke at an Iftaar dinner held at the Muslim Community Center in Silver Spring, Maryland.
* Fulfilling a pledge made by Attorney General Ashcroft at the November 27, 2001 Iftaar dinner, the Assistant Attorney General participated in a panel discussion on December 19, 2001 at the Department of Justice to answer questions about the USA Patriot Act of 2001.
Director Sharee Freeman of the Community Relations Service and senior personnel from the Office of the Deputy Attorney General, the Criminal Division, the Office of Legal Policy, the FBI, and the Immigration and Naturalization Service also participated.
* On December 20, 2001, Assistant Attorney General Boyd met with leaders of Arab-American, Muslim-American, Sikh-American, and South-Asian American organizations regarding alleged bias-motivated crimes.
* On January 26, 2002, Assistant Attorney General Boyd spoke at a luncheon sponsored by the Islamic Institute and the American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee at the Hotel Washington honoring Muslim-American New York City police officers involved in the September 11 rescue efforts.
* The Assistant Attorney General met with leaders of Pakistani-American business organizations on February 19, 2002.
* On February 26, 2002, Assistant Attorney General Boyd spoke at an outreach forum sponsored by the Center for Research Action on Race Relations in Montreal, Canada.
* On February 28, 2002, Deputy Assistant Attorney General Michael Wiggins conducted a briefing for representatives from several Pakistani-American organizations on the Civil Rights Division's enforcement and outreach efforts.
* On March 2, 2002, Assistant Attorney General Boyd gave the keynote speech at an American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee banquet in Fairfield, New Jersey.
* On March 12, 2002, Assistant Attorney General Boyd, along with Director Sharee Freeman of the Community Relations Service and Office of Intergovernmental Affairs officials, met with leaders of Arab-American, Muslim-American, and interfaith organizations.
* On May 2, 2002, the Assistant Attorney General spoke at a Capital Area Muslim Bar Association Dinner.
* On May 14, 2002, Assistant Attorney General Boyd made remarks at the First Annual Sikh Coalition Awards Dinner.
* On July 12, 2002, Assistant Attorney General Boyd attended a farewell party for Dr. Maleeha Lodhi, Pakistan's Ambassador to the United States.
